# 🌿 A Reflection — From the Body's Suffering to the Peace of the Self

**My humble pranāms to my revered Gurus, respected teachers, saints, and dear friends.**

Over the past few days, this body passed through illness, very high blood sugar, nausea, vomiting, and physical weakness. For a time, it seemed that an urgent visit to the hospital might become necessary. Many loved ones expressed sincere concern and encouraged me to seek immediate care.

By the grace of the Lord, the blessings of my Gurus, careful rest, medical guidance, and moderation, the body has become calmer. I will continue to follow my physician's advice, monitor my health closely, and care for this body as a sacred trust.

Yet this experience reminded me of an eternal truth taught by Vedānta.

The body becomes healthy.

The body becomes ill.

It grows strong.

It grows weak.

But the witnessing Self—the Chidātmā—undergoes none of these changes.

Illness did not distance me from satsang.

Instead, it gently led me back to it.

When the body becomes fragile, one discovers that every external support has its limits.

The only unfailing refuge is the Self—the ever-present, ever-free Awareness that Sage Vasiṣṭha and the Bhagavad Gītā continually point us toward.

If this brief period of suffering has deepened my remembrance of the Self even a little, then I accept it as a hidden blessing.

From the depths of my heart, I offer gratitude to my revered Gurus, dear friends, and fellow seekers for their prayers, encouragement, and loving concern.

Please continue to bless me so that, for as long as this body lives, it may remain dedicated to satsang, self-inquiry, service, and abidance in the light of the Self.

**Hari Om Tat Sat.** 🌿🕉️
